<ul class=3D"eplus-wrapper wp-block-list">
<li class=3D" eplus-wrapper">14,300,000 in the standard form is 1.43 =C3=97=
 10<sup>7</sup>.</li>



<li class=3D" eplus-wrapper">3000 in the standard form is 3 =C3=97 10=C2=B3=
.</li>



<li class=3D" eplus-wrapper">Some other examples are 1.98 =E2=9C=95 10=C2=
=B9=C2=B3 and&nbsp; 0.76 =E2=9C=95 10=C2=B9=C2=B3.</li>
</ul>



<p class=3D" eplus-wrapper">Factoid: =E2=80=9CStandard Form=E2=80=9D is als=
o called =E2=80=9CScientific Notation=E2=80=9D depending on the mathematica=
l lingo of the country you are in. In the United Kingdom and the countries =
that follow the same conventions as the United Kingdom, the term =E2=80=9CS=
cientific Notation=E2=80=9D is most commonly used whereas in countries that=
 follow the US conventions majorly refer to this form of writing as the =E2=
=80=9CStandard Form=E2=80=9D.<br></p>



<p class=3D" eplus-wrapper"><strong>Example 1: Consider the number 81,900,0=
00,000,000.</strong></p>



<p class=3D" eplus-wrapper"><strong>Step 1:</strong> Write the first number=
: <strong>8</strong>.</p>



<p class=3D" eplus-wrapper"><strong>Step 2:</strong> Add a <a href=3D"https=
://www.splashlearn.com/math-vocabulary/decimals/decimal-point" target=3D"_b=
lank" rel=3D"noopener" title=3D"">decimal point</a> after this and write th=
e remaining non-zero numbers: <strong>8.19</strong></p>



<p class=3D" eplus-wrapper"><strong>Step 3: </strong>Now count the number o=
f <a href=3D"https://www.splashlearn.com/math-vocabulary/number-sense/digit=
" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener" title=3D"">digits</a> after <strong>8.=
</strong> There are <strong>13</strong> digits. This 13 will be the power o=
f 10 while writing the given number in standard form.</p>



<p class=3D" eplus-wrapper"><strong>Step 4:</strong> So, in standard form: =
<strong>81,900,000,000,000</strong> is 8.19 =C3=97 10=C2=B9=C2=B3.</p>



