Real-Life Examples of Standard Form</h2>



<ul class=3D"eplus-wrapper wp-block-list">
<li class=3D" eplus-wrapper">The distance between the Sun and Mars is 141,7=
00,000 miles or 228,000,000 km.</li>
</ul>



<p class=3D" eplus-wrapper">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp=
;&nbsp;This distance can easily be written in standard form as:<br>        =
  1.417 =C3=97 108 miles or 2.28 =C3=97 108 km.</p>



<ul class=3D"eplus-wrapper wp-block-list">
<li class=3D" eplus-wrapper">Atoms are tiny units of matter composed of thr=
ee fundamental particles=E2=80=94proton, neutron, and electron.<br>A proton=
 and a neutron weigh equally, 1.67 =C3=97 10=E2=80=9327 kg.<br>The weight o=
f an electron is 9.11 =C3=97 10=E2=80=9331 kg.</li>
</ul>



<p class=3D" eplus-wrapper">Many other quantities, such as the size of plan=
ets, the size of microorganisms, the size of microchips, and the country=E2=
=80=99s population are all expressed in standard form.</p>



<p class=3D" eplus-wrapper"><strong>Fractions</strong></p>



<p class=3D" eplus-wrapper">A fraction is said to be in standard form when =
both the numerator and <a href=3D"https://www.splashlearn.com/math-vocabula=
ry/fractions/denominator" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener" title=3D"">den=
ominator</a> are <em>co-prime</em> numbers.</p>



<p class=3D" eplus-wrapper">Factoid: Two numbers are said to be co-prime wh=
en their only common divisor(or <a href=3D"https://www.splashlearn.com/math=
-vocabulary/multiplication/factor" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener" title=
=3D"">factor</a>) is 1. For example, 2 and 3, 4 and 9, 6 and 13. By virtue,=
 two prime numbers are always co-prime.</p>



<p class=3D" eplus-wrapper"><em>For example, </em>the fraction&nbsp; =E2=85=
=9A&nbsp; is a standard fraction because the numerator 5 and denominator 6 =
do not have only 1 as their common <a href=3D"https://www.splashlearn.com/m=
ath-vocabulary/division/divisor" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener" title=
=3D"">divisor</a>, whereas the fraction 4/8 is not a standard fraction beca=
use the numerator and denominator have common divisors other than 1, i.e., =
2 and 4.<br><br>But no worries, do you want to turn a fraction into its sta=
ndard form? We got your back.<br>Let=E2=80=99s look at an example.<br></p>



<p class=3D" eplus-wrapper">Consider the fraction 12/20.<br><br><strong>Ste=
p 1:</strong> Find all the common divisors of the numerator and the denomin=
ator.<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; In this case, 12 and 20 =
have common divisors: 1,2,4.<br></p>



<p class=3D" eplus-wrapper"><strong>Step 2:</strong> Divide the numerator a=
nd denominator by their greatest common divisor. Like this:</p>



<figure class=3D"is-style-default wp-block-image size-full eplus-wrapper"><=
img decoding=3D"async" width=3D"680" height=3D"209" src=3D"https://www.spla=
shlearn.com/math-vocabulary/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/standard_form-1-01.p=
ng" alt=3D"Division of Numerator and Denominator by Greatest Common" class=
=3D"wp-image-3739"></figure>



<p class=3D" eplus-wrapper">No Step 3 is required! As you can see =E2=85=97=
 is a standard fraction and is the standard form of 12/20.</p>



<h2 class=3D"eplus-wrapper wp-block-heading" id=3D"3-examples-of-standard-f=
orm-of-fractions-"><strong>Examples of Standard Form of Fractions</strong><=
/h2>



<ul class=3D"eplus-wrapper wp-block-list">
<li class=3D" eplus-wrapper">The most famous standard fraction is 22/7, als=
o called =E2=80=9Cpi=E2=80=9D.</li>



<li class=3D" eplus-wrapper">All <a href=3D"https://www.splashlearn.com/mat=
h-vocabulary/fractions/unit-fraction" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener" ti=
tle=3D"">unit fractions</a>, i.e., fractions with <a href=3D"https://www.sp=
lashlearn.com/math-vocabulary/division/numerator" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"=
noopener" title=3D"">numerator</a> 1 are standard.</li>
</ul>



<p class=3D" eplus-wrapper"><strong>Decimal Numbers</strong></p>



<p class=3D" eplus-wrapper">The definition for the standard form of decimal=
 numbers is the same as that of whole numbers,</p>



<p class=3D" eplus-wrapper"><em>Any number that we can write as a decimal n=
umber, between 1.0 and 10.0, multiplied by a power of 10, is said to be in =
standard form.</em></p>



<p class=3D" eplus-wrapper">The scoop about the standard form of decimal nu=
mbers lies in their steps. This is a bit different from whole numbers, wher=
e you may have noticed, the power of 10 was a positive number like in 1.23 =
=C3=97 10<sup>8</sup>.<br><br>Let=E2=80=99s see how we can convert a scary-=
looking decimal number into a pretty-looking decimal number.<br></p>



<p class=3D" eplus-wrapper">Consider the decimal number 0.0004789.</p>



<p class=3D" eplus-wrapper"><strong>Step 1:</strong> Make your decimal numb=
er jump from its original position and place it after the first non-zero di=
git: <strong>4.789</strong>.</p>



<p class=3D" eplus-wrapper"><strong>Step 2:</strong> Count the number of di=
gits you jumped. In this case, we jumped 4 digits. This number will be the =
power of 10 while writing our decimal number in standard form.</p>



<p class=3D" eplus-wrapper"><strong>Step 3:</strong> If you have made jumps=
 in the direction to the right, the power of 10 will be negative. If you ma=
de the jumps in the direction to the left, the power of 10 will be positive=
.</p>



<p class=3D" eplus-wrapper"><strong>Step 4:</strong> So, in standard form: =
<strong>0.0004789</strong> is <strong>4.789 =C3=97 10<sup>-4</sup></strong>=
.</p>



<p class=3D" eplus-wrapper">Using the same method, the standard form of the=
 decimal number <strong>981.23</strong> will be&nbsp;</p>



<p class=3D" eplus-wrapper"><strong>9.8123 =C3=97 10</strong><strong><sup>2=
</sup></strong>.</p>



<p class=3D" eplus-wrapper">The standard form of mathematical elements allo=
ws us to work in a convenient and efficient manner by making them easily re=
adable for everyone. There is no shortcut to finding the standard form of a=
nything, but here are a few tips and tricks that we have summarized for you=
 that you must keep in mind while writing something in standard form.</p>



<h2 class=3D"eplus-wrapper wp-block-heading" id=3D"4-tips-to-master-standar=
d-form">Tips to Master Standard Form</h2>



<ul class=3D"eplus-wrapper wp-block-list">
<li class=3D" eplus-wrapper">Thoroughly understand the two parts of the sta=
ndard form: digits and the power of 10.</li>



<li class=3D" eplus-wrapper">Remember that the power is negative if you hav=
e made jumps to the right and the power is positive when you have made jump=
s to the left while putting a decimal number in its standard form.</li>



<li class=3D" eplus-wrapper">Count the places you have moved the decimal po=
int twice before writing the final answer.</li>



<li class=3D" eplus-wrapper">Don=E2=80=99t forget about the second cousin o=
f prime numbers: the co-primes. They are the basics of putting a fraction i=
n its standard form.</li>
</ul>



<h2 class=3D"eplus-wrapper wp-block-heading" id=3D"5-solved-examples-of-sta=
ndard-form">Solved Examples of Standard Form</h2>



<p class=3D" eplus-wrapper"><strong>Express 321,000,000 in scientific notat=
ion.</strong></p>



<p class=3D" eplus-wrapper">The scientific form of the number is 3.21 x 10<=
sup>8</sup>.</p>



<p class=3D" eplus-wrapper"><strong>Express 0.00005432 in the standard form=
.</strong></p>



<p class=3D" eplus-wrapper">The scientific form of the number is 5.432 x 10=
<sup>-5</sup>.</p>



<p class=3D" eplus-wrapper"><strong>Write 25/40 in the standard form.</stro=
ng></p>



<p class=3D" eplus-wrapper">The scientific form of the given fraction is =
=E2=85=9D.</p>



